und.com/news/millercoors-acquires-majority-stake-terrapin-beer-company|title=MillerCoors Acquires Majority Stake in Terrapin Beer Company {{!}} Brewbound.com|website=Brewbound.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-11}}</ref>\n|United Distributors\n|-\n|The Cannon Brew Pub<ref name=\":0\" />\n|Columbus\n|\n|Brewpub\n|\n|\n|-\n| Three Taverns Craft Brewery  || Decatur || 2013 || Brewery || 2,500<ref name=\"clatl.com\"/>\n|Savannah Distributing\n|-\n|Torched Hop Brewing<ref name=\":0\" />\n|Atlanta\n|2016\n|Brewery\n|\n|Liberator Distributing\n|-\n| Twains Billiards and Tap || Decatur || 2006 || Brewpub || 750<ref>{{cite web|title=Brews Travelers 365|url=http://brewstravelers365.com/2014/02/22/48-twains-billiards-tap-in-decatur-ga/|accessdate=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n|Savannah Distributing\n|-\n|Wild Heaven Craft Beers\n|Avondale Estates \n|2010 \n|Brewery \n|7,000<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlantamagazine.com/drinks/cant-find-six-pack-tropicalia-anywhere/|title=Why you can't find a six-pack of Tropic\u00e1lia anywhere - Atlanta Magazine|date=2016-12-06|newspaper=Atlanta Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2017-01-11}}</ref>\n|Georgia Crown\n|-\n|Wild Leap Brew Co.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lagrangenews.com/2017/01/13/a-wild-leap-for-downtown/|title=A \u2018Wild Leap\u2019 for downtown {{!}} LaGrange Daily News|website=www.lagrangenews.com|access-date=2017-05-16}}</ref>\n|LaGrange\n|2017\n|Brewery\n|\n|Atlanta Beverage Company\n|-\n|Wrecking Bar Brewpub<ref name=\":0\" />\n|Atlanta\n|\n|Brewpub\n|\n|United Distributors\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Beer in the United States]]\n* [[List of breweries in the United States]]\n* [[List of microbreweries]]\n\n{{Portalbar|Beer|Drink|Companies|Georgia_(U.S._state)}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n<!--Navigation boxes-->\n{{Lists of United States breweries}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breweries In Georgia (U.S. State), List Of}}\n[[Category:Beer brewing companies based in Georgia (U.S. state)|*]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state)-related lists]]\n[[Category:Lists of breweries in the United States|Georgia]]\n[[Category:Lists of companies based in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{more citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n\n'''Breweries in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]''' produce a wide range of [[beer]]s in different [[beer styles|styles]] that are marketed locally, regionally and nationally.\n\nIn 2012 Georgia's 29 breweries and brewpubs employed 1650 people directly, and more than 31,000 others in related jobs such as wholesaling and retailing.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brewer's Almanac--Active Brewer Permits, 2004 - 2012|url=http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/beer-statistics|publisher=The Beer Institute|accessdate=19 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140516153451/http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/beer-statistics|archivedate=16 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"The Beer Institute\">{{cite web|title=The Economic Impact of the Beer Industry--State Legislative & Congressional District Data, Georgia|url=http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/economic-impact|publisher=The Beer Institute|accessdate=19 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203091325/http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/economic-impact|archivedate=3 February 2014}}</ref> Including people directly employed in brewing, as well as those who supply Georgia's breweries with everything from ingredients to machinery, the total business and personal tax revenue generated by Georgia's breweries and related industries was more than $1.4 billion.<ref name=\"The Beer Institute\"/> Consumer purchases of Georgia's brewery products generated another $366 million in tax revenue.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Economic Impact of the Beer Industry--2012 Data, Georgia|url=http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/economic-impact|publisher=The Beer Institute|accessdate=19 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203091325/http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/economic-impact|archivedate=3 February 2014}}</ref> In 2012, according to the [[Brewers Association]], Georgia ranked 48th in the number of [[Microbrewery#Craft brewing|craft breweries]] per capita, with 24.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brewersassociation.org/attachments/0000/6291/Capita_perbrewery.pdf|publisher=Brewers Association|title=Capita per Brewery|accessdate=19 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor context, at the end of 2013 there were 2,822 [[brewery|breweries]] in the United States, including 2,768 craft breweries subdivided into 1,237 [[Microbrewery#Brewpub|brewpubs]], 1,412 [[Microbrewery|microbreweries]] and 119 regional craft breweries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brewers Association Announces 2013 Craft Brewer Growth|url=http://www.brewersassociation.org/pages/media/press-releases/show?title=brewers-association-announces-2013-craft-brewer-growth|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref>  In that same year, according to the [[Beer Institute]], the brewing industry employed around 43,000 Americans in brewing and distribution and had a combined economic impact of more than $246 billion.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beer Serves America|url=http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/economic-impact|publisher=The Beer Institute|accessdate=14 May 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203091325/http://www.beerinstitute.org/br/economic-impact/economic-impact|archivedate=3 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Georgia breweries==\n{{dynamic list}}\n\n===Historic===\n1738 - first brewery in Georgia;{{According to whom|date=September 2015}} Major William Horton, aide to [[James Oglethorpe]], administers Jekyll Island; his residence, [[Horton House]], includes a brewery supplying beer to soldiers and settlers in the area\n\n===Current===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Georgia breweries, brewpubs, and client brewers in current operation\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Name\n! scope=\"co