{"title_page": "Eric Djemba-Djemba", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Eric Djemba-Djemba (so good he's named twice)\n| image          = Eric Djemba-Djemba (2008).jpg\n| image_size     = 200px\n| caption        = Djemba-Djemba playing for [[Odense Boldklub|OB]] in 2008\n| fullname       = Eric Daniel Djemba-Djemba<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|5206|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1981|5|4|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n| birth_place    = [[Douala]], Cameroon\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=11}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[FC Vallorbe-Ballaigues]]<ref>[http://www.givemesport.com/909792-eric-djembadjemba-signs-for-fifth-division-swiss-club Eric Djemba-Djemba signs for fifth division Swiss club]\u201a givemesport.com, 6 November 2016</ref>\n| clubnumber     = 19\n| years1         = 2001\u20132003\n|clubs1  = [[FC Nantes|Nantes]]\n|caps1  = 42\n|goals1  = 1\n| years2         = 2003\u20132005\n|clubs2  = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|caps2  = 20\n|goals2  = 0\n| years3         = 2005\u20132007\n|clubs3  = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n|caps3  = 11\n|goals3  = 0\n| years4         = 2007\n|clubs4  = \u2192 [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] (loan)\n|caps4  = 15\n|goals4  = 0\n| years5         = 2007\u20132008\n|clubs5  = [[Qatar SC]]\n|caps5  = 26\n|goals5  = 3\n| years6         = 2008\u20132012\n|clubs6  = [[Odense Boldklub|OB]]\n|caps6  = 102\n|goals6  = 3\n| years7         = 2012\u20132013\n|clubs7  = [[Hapoel Tel Aviv F.C.|Hapoel Tel Aviv]]\n|caps7  = 28\n|goals7  = 0\n| years8         = 2013\n|clubs8  = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|caps8  = 16\n|goals8  = 0\n| years9         = 2014\n|clubs9  = [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]\n|caps9  = 2\n|goals9  = 0\n| years10        = 2014\u20132015\n|clubs10 = [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]]\n|caps10 = 9\n|goals10 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132011\n|nationalteam1 = [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]]\n|nationalcaps1 = 34\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n| years11        = 2015\n|clubs11 = [[Bhayangkara F.C.|Persebaya Bhayangkara]]\n|caps11 = 8\n|goals11 = 4\n|caps12 = 34\n|goals12 = 25\n| years13        = 2016\n|clubs13 =   [[Voltigeurs de Ch\u00e2teaubriant|Ch\u00e2teaubriant]]\n| years14        = 2016\u2013\n|clubs14 = FC Vallorbe-Ballaigues\n|caps14 = 9\n|goals14 = 1\n| pcupdate       = 16:57, 30 January 2015 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Eric Daniel Djemba-Djemba''' (born 4 May 1981) is a Cameroonian [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for Swiss fifth division club FC Vallorbe-Ballaigues. He has previously played club football in France, England, Qatar, Denmark, Israel, Scotland, India, Indonesia and Serbia. In international competition, he represented [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], having appeared for his country 34 times, including at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Nantes===\nDjemba-Djemba rose to prominence with Nantes in France, where he forged a successful partnership with [[Mathieu Berson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11677/2340544/ |title=Berson going nowhere |accessdate=21 October 2013 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=31 January 2011}}</ref> His impressive performances as a feisty and uncompromising tackler for the French club earned him a dream move to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] for [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]3.5&nbsp;million in the summer of 2003, signed by [[Alex Ferguson]] as a possible eventual successor to the 31-year-old [[Roy Keane]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Buckingham |title=United sign Djemba-Djemba |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11667/2269695/ |work=Sky Sports |publisher=BSkyB |accessdate=1 September 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Manchester United===\nArriving in England, Djemba-Djemba was unknown to many fans and pundits alike. He established his aggressive style on his debut against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the [[FA Community Shield]], with a tackle on Arsenal's [[Sol Campbell]] which [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] called \"obscene\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Davies |title=It's business as usual as for Wenger and Arsenal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2409616/Its-business-as-usual-as-for-Wenger-and-Arsenal.html |work=Telegraph.co.uk |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=16 August 2003 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 18 months at [[Old Trafford]], Djemba-Djemba found it difficult to maintain a period of sustained form, and he was eventually unable to establish himself as a player capable of filling captain [[Roy Keane]]'s shoes. A highlight during his United career was when he scored a looping volley against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]. With the score at 2\u20132 and 3 minutes of extra time left, [[Quinton Fortune]] swung in a corner which reached Djemba-Djemba, who hit it first time and it looped over Leeds goalkeeper [[Paul Robinson (goalkeeper)|Paul Robinson]] which secured a 3\u20132 win and progression to the next round.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leeds 2\u20133 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3204813.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=28 October 2003 |accessdate=16 September 2009 }}</ref> He scored only once more for United, in a 5\u20130 [[UEFA Champions League]] win over Greek side [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd wreak Greek havoc |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/3109724.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=16 September 2003 |accessdate=3 November 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Aston Villa===\nDjemba-Djemba was sold to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in the January 2005 transfer window for a fee of \u00a31.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/4221969.stm |title=Djemba-Djemba wraps up Villa move |publisher=BBC |date=31 January 2005 |accessdate=21 October 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306121900/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/4221969.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> However, the move did little to restore the player's reputation as he found it difficult to move ahead of [[Gavin McCann]] and [[Steven Davis]] in Villa's midfield. After being played only once, as a late substitute against Arsenal in the first ever game at the [[Emirates Stadium]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Austin |title=Arsenal 1\u20131 Aston Villa |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4786655.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 August 2006 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> by new Villa manager [[Martin O'Neill]] on the first day of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307 season]], Djemba-Djemba was loaned out to Championship club Burnley for the remainder of the season in the January transfer window.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/burnley/6255757.stm |title=Burnley seal Djemba-Djemba loan |publisher=BBC |date=12 January 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307084733/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/burnley/6255757.stm |archivedate=7 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Burnley ====\nDjemba-Djemba made his first appearance for Burnley on 13 January 2007 against [[Southampton FC|Southampton]], playing the full 90 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/6236747.stm |title=Southampton 0\u20130 Burnley |publisher=BBC |date=13 January 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> Early in his time at [[Turf Moor]], Djemba-Djemba was sent off for the [[Lancashire]] side after a second bookable offence at [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/jan/31/match.derbycounty |title=Managers sent to the stands as Howard keeps Derby soaring |publisher=The Guardian |date=31 January 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> however he impressed with his skillful and effective play during his loan spell.\n\nDuring July 2007, all signs pointed to Djemba-Djemba leaving [[Villa Park]] after he was the only member of the first-team squad not to be included in the [[North American]] tour and on 2 August 2007,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/now-eric-djemba-djemba-289626 |title=Where are they now? Eric Djemba-Djemba |publisher=Birmingham Mail |date=6 November 2012 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> his contract was terminated by Aston Villa.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-472873/Djemba-Djemba-released-Villa.html |title=Djemba-Djemba released by Villa |publisher=Daily Mail |date=3 August 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/djembadjemba-released-by-villa-6603167.html |title=Djemba-Djemba released by Villa |publisher=London Evening Standard |date=3 August 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[Daily Mail]] placed Djemba-Djemba thirteen as the biggest transfer flops in Premier League history.<ref>{{cite news|title=THE LIST: The biggest transfer flops in Premier League history Nos 20\u201311|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1181333/THE-LIST-The-biggest-transfer-flops-Premier-League-history-Nos-20-11.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Qatar SC===\nFollowing his departure from [[Aston Villa]], Djemba-Djemba joined [[Qatar SC]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Premier League Rumour Mill: West Ham want Brazilian wonderkid|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-484203/Premier-League-Rumour-Mill-West-Ham-want-Brazilian-wonderkid.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=27 September 2007|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> He only played one season at the [[Qatar]]-based club, but managed to get his football career back on track.\n\n===Odense BK===\nOn 16 July 2008, Djemba-Djemba signed a three-year contract with Danish outfit [[Odense Boldklub]], the contract was later extended with a year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-Red Devil joins Odense|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/3844950/ex-red-devil-joins-odense|publisher=Sky Sports|date=20 July 2008|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> He previously went on a trial with the club<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidligere Man United-spiller til pr\u00f8vetr\u00e6ning i OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/fodbold/tidligere-man-united-spiller-til-proevetraening-i-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=15 July 2008|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> and made his Odense debut against former club Aston Villa in the [[Intertoto Cup]]. Odense drew the match 1\u20131, losing 2\u20131 on aggregate. In his career in Odense, Djemba-Djemba has impressed the club's fans, with his good ball skills and great performances.<ref>{{cite news|title=Payback time for Djemba-Djemba|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1038716/Payback-time-Djemba-Djemba.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=25 July 2008|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> In his first season as an Odense player, he played tremendous football and was by many called the league's best player.{{by whom|date=July 2012}} In 2009, in the 72nd minute against [[Esbjerg fB|Esbjerg fb]] away, Djemba-Djemba became the first player in the Danish league to assist with his sock, as the sole of his right boot had come off, forcing him to finish the game with one boot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ob.dk/artikel/ob-sejrede-paa-nyt-stadion.aspx|title=OB sejrede p\u00e5 nyt stadion|website=www.ob.dk|access-date=2016-08-11}}</ref> Later that year, Djemba-Djemba was among three other players to be nominated for the SAS Liga player of the year.<ref>{{cite news|title=[Three foreigners can be player of the year]|url=http://www.bold.dk/nyt/Tre-udlaendinge-kan-blive-aarets-spiller|publisher=Bold.dk|language=Danish|date=5 October 2009|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2010, Djemba-Djemba was linked a move back to England by joining [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Brom]] and Italian side [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Italienere lurer p\u00e5 Djemba-Djemba|url=http://www.bold.dk/nyt/Italienere-lurer-paa-Djemba-Djemba|publisher=Bold.dsk|language=Danish|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba in Baggies link|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6279731/djemba-djemba-in-baggies-link|publisher=Sky Sorts|date=26 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> After traveling to England for transfer talk, the move was broken down and this led accusations against West Brom by the club and Djemba-Djemba, himself.<ref>{{cite news|title=Baggies end Djemba interest|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6283155/baggies-end-djemba-interest|publisher=Sky Sports|date=28 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Odense refute Baggies claims|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6284604/odense-refute-baggies-claims|publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba blasts Baggies|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6289684/djemba-djemba-blasts-baggies|publisher=Sky Sports|date=1 August 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2011\u201312 season, Djemba-Djemba's future at OB was uncertain after his contract expired. Despite expected negotiations,<ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba: M\u00e5ske forl\u00e6nger jeg med OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/oevrig-sport/djemba-djemba-maaske-forlaenger-jeg-med-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=23 August 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba vil forl\u00e6nge med OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/superligaen/djemba-djemba-vil-forlaenge-med-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=15 May 2012|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> Djemba-Djemba instead left the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mendy og Djemba-Djemba forlader OB|url=http://www.bold.dk/nyt/Mendy-og-Djemba-Djemba-forlader-OB|publisher=Bold.dk|language=Danish|date=24 May 2012|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> The year before, Djemba-Djemba, along with [[Peter Utaka]], had been told by the club's officials that their contracts would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Avis: Djemba-Djemba og Utaka forlader OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/superligaen/avis-djemba-djemba-og-utaka-forlader-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> As a result of their contracts not being renewed, the club decided to release players sooner rather than later.<ref>{{cite news|title=OB: Overvejer salg af Utaka og Djemba|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Hapoel Tel Aviv===\nOn 14 August 2012, Djemba-Djemba signed a two-year contract with Israeli club [[Hapoel Tel Aviv F.C.|Hapoel Tel Aviv]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Djemba-Djemba signed for Hapoel: I found a warm home |url=http://www.one.co.il/Article/204294.html |language=Hebrew |publisher=ONE |date=14 August 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2012 }}</ref> Djemba-Djemba played a total of 28 league games with the [[Tel Aviv]]-based team.\n\n===Partizan===\nOn 24 July 2013, Djemba-Djemba signed a two-year contract with [[Serbia]]n side [[FK Partizan|Partizan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0110emba \u0110emba potpisao za \u0160ampione |url=http://www.sr.partizan.rs/67900-67900/ |language=Serbian |publisher=partizan.rs |date=24 July 2013 |accessdate=24 July 2013}}</ref> He made his debut in a Champions League qualifying match away to [[PFC Ludogorets Razgrad|Ludogorets Razgrad]] on 31 July 2013, coming on as a substitute in the 64th minute.<ref>http://www.mozzartsport.com/vesti/sale-buljavi-brate-moj</ref> However, Djemba-Djemba hardly played for Partizan during the first half of the season. The club's signing of [[Nikola Drin\u010di\u0107]] on 20 December meant that Djemba-Djemba became surplus to requirements and his contract was terminated on 23 December 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Partizan raskinuo ugovor sa \u0110emba \u0110embom |trans-title=Partizan terminated the contract with Djemba Djemba |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/sport.294.html:469954-Partizan-raskinuo-ugovor-sa-Djemba-Djembom |work=Novosti.rs |publisher=Kompanija Novosti |date=23 December 2013 |accessdate=23 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nUpon joining St Mirren, Djemba-Djemba once went on three month unpaid at the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren midfielder Eric Djemba-Djemba keen to extend his stay in Scottish football|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/st-mirren-midfielder-eric-djemba-djemba-3222651?|publisher=Daily Record|date=9 March 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===St Mirren===\nOn 5 February 2014, Djemba-Djemba signed a short-term deal with [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Saints sign Djemba-Djemba |url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=30679 |publisher=saintmirren.net |date=5 February 2014 |accessdate=5 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221233146/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=30679 |archivedate=21 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He has said he hopes his move to St Mirren can help him gain a place in the [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] in [[Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Djemba-Djemba hopes St Miren move can force a World cup place |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/st-mirren/263108-eric-djemba-djemba-hopes-st-mirren-move-can-force-a-world-cup-place/ |publisher=STV Sport |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014 }}</ref> Upon joining the club, Manager [[Danny Lennon]] described Djemba-Djemba as the club's biggest signing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eric Djemba Djemba is St Mirren's biggest signing ever according to manager Danny Lennon|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/458429/Eric-Djemba-Djemba-is-St-Mirren-s-biggest-signing-ever-according-to-manager-Danny-Lennon|publisher=Daily Express|date=6 February 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nDjemba-Djemba made his debut for the club, in the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Cup#Fifth round|fifth round of the Scottish Cup]], as St Mirren lost 2\u20131 against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]. After making just three appearances in all competitions, Djemba-Djemba was released by the club at the end of the season and also failed to secure a place on the Cameroon squad for the world cup.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27492630 | title=St Mirren: Eric Djemba-Djemba among Buddies departures | publisher=bbc.co.uk | date=20 May 2014 | accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Chennaiyin FC===\nIn October 2014, Djemba-Djemba signed a short-term deal with [[Indian Super League]] club [[Chennaiyin FC]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Prasad|first1=Vishnu|title=Former United Star Joins Chennaiyin in Late Movement|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/Former-United-Star-Joins-Chennaiyin-in-Late-Movement/2014/10/20/article2486275.ece|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=28 October 2014|date=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Persebaya Bhayangkara===\nIn February 2015, Djemba-Djemba signed for [[Indonesian Super League]] club Persebaya Bhayangkara.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ini Nilai Kontrak Eric Djemba-Djemba Di Persebaya Surabaya |trans-title= |first=Farabi |last=Firdausy |work=Goal |date=3 February 2015 |access-date=29 December 2018 |url= https://www.goal.com/id/news/1391/liga-1-indonesia/2015/02/03/8567132/ini-nilai-kontrak-eric-djemba-djemba-di-persebaya-surabaya |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Eric Djemba-Djemba Akhirnya Gabung Latihan Persebaya |work=TRIBUNnews.com |date=4 February 2015 |accessdate=29 December 2018 |url= http://www.tribunnews.com/superball/2015/02/04/eric-djemba-djemba-akhirnya-gabung-latihan-persebaya}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nDjemba-Djemba was a member of the [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon team]] that won the [[2002 African Nations Cup]] and finished as runners-up to France at the [[2003 FIFA Confederations Cup]]. While in the Confederations Cup, Djemba-Djemba revealed that he was the last person to have a conversation with [[Marc-Vivien Fo\u00e9]] before Fo\u00e9 collapsed on the pitch and later died in the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren's Eric Djemba-Djemba on Marc-Vivien Foe|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/st-mirren-s-eric-djemba-djemba-on-marc-vivien-foe-1-3299667|publisher=The Scotsman|date=9 February 2014|accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref> He also appeared at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]]. However, Djemba-Djemba wasn't included for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], due to managerial differences.<ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba kommer ikke til VM|url=http://www.bt.dk/fodbold/djemba-djemba-kommer-ikke-til-vm|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> Despite his attempt to make the Cameroon squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]], Djemba-Djemba wasn't included in the 28-man provisional World Cup squad and thus missing out on the World Cup under the management of [[Volker Finke]].<ref>{{cite news|title=World Cup 2014: Cameroon coach picks familiar line-up|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27374746|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 May 2014|accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDjemba-Djemba was born in [[Douala]], Cameroon.<ref name=Hugman/> He was declared bankrupt following his move from Manchester United to Aston Villa in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ten 4x4s, 30 bank accounts...but Eric lost it all|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-484203/Premier-League-Rumour-Mill-West-Ham-want-Brazilian-wonderkid.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=13 March 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nDjemba-Djemba was married and fathered four children before being divorced.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eric Djemba-Djemba was on \u00a375k-a-month at Man United.. but every penny was going on loan repayments, reveals St Mirren new boy's ex-agent|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/eric-djemba-djemba-75k-a-month-man-united-3116850|publisher=Daily Record|date=6 February 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> Djemba-Djemba is a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref>{{cite news |title=St Mirren new boy Eric Djemba-Djemba: I've lost millions.. but now I'm a simple man who takes the train and eats at KFC and enjoys sea bass on occasion. |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/st-mirren-new-boy-eric-3120241 |publisher=Daily Record |date=7 February 2014 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n;Manchester United\n*[[FA Cup]]: [[2004 FA Cup Final|2003\u201304]]\n*[[FA Community Shield]]: [[2003 FA Community Shield|2003]]\n\n===International===\n;Cameroon\n*[[Africa Cup of Nations]]: [[2002 African Cup of Nations|2002]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu|299}}\n* [http://www.danskfodbold.com/spiller.php?ligaid=2001&spillerid=11165 Career statistics] at danskfodbold.com {{in lang|da}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{Soccerway|eric-djemba-djemba/2805}}\n* {{NFT|1255<!-- /Eric_Djemba_Djemba -->}}\n* {{UEFA player}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|bg = Green\n|fg = Yellow\n|title = Cameroon squads\n|list1 =\n{{Cameroon Squad 2002 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Cameroon Squad 2002 World Cup}}\n{{Cameroon Squad Confederations Cup 2003}}\n{{Cameroon Squad 2004 African Nations Cup}}\n{{Cameroon Squad 2006 Africa Cup of Nations}}}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Djemba-Djemba, Eric}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Douala]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian Christians]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian footballers]]\n[[Category:Cameroon international footballers]]\n[[Category:Kadji Sports Academy players]]\n[[Category:FC Nantes players]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Qatar SC players]]\n[[Category:Odense Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Hapoel Tel Aviv F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FK Partizan players]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chennaiyin FC players]]\n[[Category:Persebaya Surabaya players]]\n[[Category:Voltigeurs de Ch\u00e2teaubriant players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Israeli Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Serbian SuperLiga players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League players]]\n[[Category:Liga 1 (Indonesia) players]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2003 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:2002 African Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2004 African Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2006 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Israel]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Israel]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Eric Djemba-Djemba\n| image          = Eric Djemba-Djemba (2008).jpg\n| image_size     = 200px\n| caption        = Djemba-Djemba playing for [[Odense Boldklub|OB]] in 2008\n| fullname       = Eric Daniel Djemba-Djemba<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|5206|accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1981|5|4|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n| birth_place    = [[Douala]], Cameroon\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=11}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[FC Vallorbe-Ballaigues]]<ref>[http://www.givemesport.com/909792-eric-djembadjemba-signs-for-fifth-division-swiss-club Eric Djemba-Djemba signs for fifth division Swiss club]\u201a givemesport.com, 6 November 2016</ref>\n| clubnumber     = 19\n| years1         = 2001\u20132003\n|clubs1  = [[FC Nantes|Nantes]]\n|caps1  = 42\n|goals1  = 1\n| years2         = 2003\u20132005\n|clubs2  = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|caps2  = 20\n|goals2  = 0\n| years3         = 2005\u20132007\n|clubs3  = [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n|caps3  = 11\n|goals3  = 0\n| years4         = 2007\n|clubs4  = \u2192 [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] (loan)\n|caps4  = 15\n|goals4  = 0\n| years5         = 2007\u20132008\n|clubs5  = [[Qatar SC]]\n|caps5  = 26\n|goals5  = 3\n| years6         = 2008\u20132012\n|clubs6  = [[Odense Boldklub|OB]]\n|caps6  = 102\n|goals6  = 3\n| years7         = 2012\u20132013\n|clubs7  = [[Hapoel Tel Aviv F.C.|Hapoel Tel Aviv]]\n|caps7  = 28\n|goals7  = 0\n| years8         = 2013\n|clubs8  = [[FK Partizan|Partizan]]\n|caps8  = 16\n|goals8  = 0\n| years9         = 2014\n|clubs9  = [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]]\n|caps9  = 2\n|goals9  = 0\n| years10        = 2014\u20132015\n|clubs10 = [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]]\n|caps10 = 9\n|goals10 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132011\n|nationalteam1 = [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]]\n|nationalcaps1 = 34\n|nationalgoals1 = 0\n| years11        = 2015\n|clubs11 = [[Bhayangkara F.C.|Persebaya Bhayangkara]]\n|caps11 = 8\n|goals11 = 4\n|caps12 = 34\n|goals12 = 25\n| years13        = 2016\n|clubs13 =   [[Voltigeurs de Ch\u00e2teaubriant|Ch\u00e2teaubriant]]\n| years14        = 2016\u2013\n|clubs14 = FC Vallorbe-Ballaigues\n|caps14 = 9\n|goals14 = 1\n| pcupdate       = 16:57, 30 January 2015 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Eric Daniel Djemba-Djemba''' (born 4 May 1981) is a Cameroonian [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for Swiss fifth division club FC Vallorbe-Ballaigues. He has previously played club football in France, England, Qatar, Denmark, Israel, Scotland, India, Indonesia and Serbia. In international competition, he represented [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], having appeared for his country 34 times, including at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Nantes===\nDjemba-Djemba rose to prominence with Nantes in France, where he forged a successful partnership with [[Mathieu Berson]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11677/2340544/ |title=Berson going nowhere |accessdate=21 October 2013 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=31 January 2011}}</ref> His impressive performances as a feisty and uncompromising tackler for the French club earned him a dream move to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] for [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]3.5&nbsp;million in the summer of 2003, signed by [[Alex Ferguson]] as a possible eventual successor to the 31-year-old [[Roy Keane]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Mark |last=Buckingham |title=United sign Djemba-Djemba |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11667/2269695/ |work=Sky Sports |publisher=BSkyB |accessdate=1 September 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Manchester United===\nArriving in England, Djemba-Djemba was unknown to many fans and pundits alike. He established his aggressive style on his debut against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the [[FA Community Shield]], with a tackle on Arsenal's [[Sol Campbell]] which [[Ars\u00e8ne Wenger]] called \"obscene\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Davies |title=It's business as usual as for Wenger and Arsenal |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2409616/Its-business-as-usual-as-for-Wenger-and-Arsenal.html |work=Telegraph.co.uk |publisher=Telegraph Media Group |date=16 August 2003 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 18 months at [[Old Trafford]], Djemba-Djemba found it difficult to maintain a period of sustained form, and he was eventually unable to establish himself as a player capable of filling captain [[Roy Keane]]'s shoes. A highlight during his United career was when he scored a looping volley against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]. With the score at 2\u20132 and 3 minutes of extra time left, [[Quinton Fortune]] swung in a corner which reached Djemba-Djemba, who hit it first time and it looped over Leeds goalkeeper [[Paul Robinson (goalkeeper)|Paul Robinson]] which secured a 3\u20132 win and progression to the next round.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leeds 2\u20133 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3204813.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=28 October 2003 |accessdate=16 September 2009 }}</ref> He scored only once more for United, in a 5\u20130 [[UEFA Champions League]] win over Greek side [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd wreak Greek havoc |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/champions_league/3109724.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=16 September 2003 |accessdate=3 November 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===Aston Villa===\nDjemba-Djemba was sold to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in the January 2005 transfer window for a fee of \u00a31.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/4221969.stm |title=Djemba-Djemba wraps up Villa move |publisher=BBC |date=31 January 2005 |accessdate=21 October 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306121900/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/a/aston_villa/4221969.stm |archivedate=6 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> However, the move did little to restore the player's reputation as he found it difficult to move ahead of [[Gavin McCann]] and [[Steven Davis]] in Villa's midfield. After being played only once, as a late substitute against Arsenal in the first ever game at the [[Emirates Stadium]],<ref>{{cite news |first=Simon |last=Austin |title=Arsenal 1\u20131 Aston Villa |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4786655.stm |work=BBC Sport |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation |date=20 August 2006 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> by new Villa manager [[Martin O'Neill]] on the first day of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006\u201307 season]], Djemba-Djemba was loaned out to Championship club Burnley for the remainder of the season in the January transfer window.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/burnley/6255757.stm |title=Burnley seal Djemba-Djemba loan |publisher=BBC |date=12 January 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307084733/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/b/burnley/6255757.stm |archivedate=7 March 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n====Loan to Burnley ====\nDjemba-Djemba made his first appearance for Burnley on 13 January 2007 against [[Southampton FC|Southampton]], playing the full 90 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/6236747.stm |title=Southampton 0\u20130 Burnley |publisher=BBC |date=13 January 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> Early in his time at [[Turf Moor]], Djemba-Djemba was sent off for the [[Lancashire]] side after a second bookable offence at [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/jan/31/match.derbycounty |title=Managers sent to the stands as Howard keeps Derby soaring |publisher=The Guardian |date=31 January 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> however he impressed with his skillful and effective play during his loan spell.\n\nDuring July 2007, all signs pointed to Djemba-Djemba leaving [[Villa Park]] after he was the only member of the first-team squad not to be included in the [[North American]] tour and on 2 August 2007,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/now-eric-djemba-djemba-289626 |title=Where are they now? Eric Djemba-Djemba |publisher=Birmingham Mail |date=6 November 2012 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref> his contract was terminated by Aston Villa.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-472873/Djemba-Djemba-released-Villa.html |title=Djemba-Djemba released by Villa |publisher=Daily Mail |date=3 August 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/djembadjemba-released-by-villa-6603167.html |title=Djemba-Djemba released by Villa |publisher=London Evening Standard |date=3 August 2007 |accessdate=21 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[Daily Mail]] placed Djemba-Djemba thirteen as the biggest transfer flops in Premier League history.<ref>{{cite news|title=THE LIST: The biggest transfer flops in Premier League history Nos 20\u201311|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1181333/THE-LIST-The-biggest-transfer-flops-Premier-League-history-Nos-20-11.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Qatar SC===\nFollowing his departure from [[Aston Villa]], Djemba-Djemba joined [[Qatar SC]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{cite news|title=Premier League Rumour Mill: West Ham want Brazilian wonderkid|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-484203/Premier-League-Rumour-Mill-West-Ham-want-Brazilian-wonderkid.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=27 September 2007|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> He only played one season at the [[Qatar]]-based club, but managed to get his football career back on track.\n\n===Odense BK===\nOn 16 July 2008, Djemba-Djemba signed a three-year contract with Danish outfit [[Odense Boldklub]], the contract was later extended with a year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-Red Devil joins Odense|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/3844950/ex-red-devil-joins-odense|publisher=Sky Sports|date=20 July 2008|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> He previously went on a trial with the club<ref>{{cite news|title=Tidligere Man United-spiller til pr\u00f8vetr\u00e6ning i OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/fodbold/tidligere-man-united-spiller-til-proevetraening-i-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=15 July 2008|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> and made his Odense debut against former club Aston Villa in the [[Intertoto Cup]]. Odense drew the match 1\u20131, losing 2\u20131 on aggregate. In his career in Odense, Djemba-Djemba has impressed the club's fans, with his good ball skills and great performances.<ref>{{cite news|title=Payback time for Djemba-Djemba|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1038716/Payback-time-Djemba-Djemba.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=25 July 2008|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> In his first season as an Odense player, he played tremendous football and was by many called the league's best player.{{by whom|date=July 2012}} In 2009, in the 72nd minute against [[Esbjerg fB|Esbjerg fb]] away, Djemba-Djemba became the first player in the Danish league to assist with his sock, as the sole of his right boot had come off, forcing him to finish the game with one boot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ob.dk/artikel/ob-sejrede-paa-nyt-stadion.aspx|title=OB sejrede p\u00e5 nyt stadion|website=www.ob.dk|access-date=2016-08-11}}</ref> Later that year, Djemba-Djemba was among three other players to be nominated for the SAS Liga player of the year.<ref>{{cite news|title=[Three foreigners can be player of the year]|url=http://www.bold.dk/nyt/Tre-udlaendinge-kan-blive-aarets-spiller|publisher=Bold.dk|language=Danish|date=5 October 2009|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2010, Djemba-Djemba was linked a move back to England by joining [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Brom]] and Italian side [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Italienere lurer p\u00e5 Djemba-Djemba|url=http://www.bold.dk/nyt/Italienere-lurer-paa-Djemba-Djemba|publisher=Bold.dsk|language=Danish|date=12 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba in Baggies link|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6279731/djemba-djemba-in-baggies-link|publisher=Sky Sorts|date=26 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> After traveling to England for transfer talk, the move was broken down and this led accusations against West Brom by the club and Djemba-Djemba, himself.<ref>{{cite news|title=Baggies end Djemba interest|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6283155/baggies-end-djemba-interest|publisher=Sky Sports|date=28 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Odense refute Baggies claims|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6284604/odense-refute-baggies-claims|publisher=Sky Sports|date=29 July 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba blasts Baggies|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11797/6289684/djemba-djemba-blasts-baggies|publisher=Sky Sports|date=1 August 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the 2011\u201312 season, Djemba-Djemba's future at OB was uncertain after his contract expired. Despite expected negotiations,<ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba: M\u00e5ske forl\u00e6nger jeg med OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/oevrig-sport/djemba-djemba-maaske-forlaenger-jeg-med-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=23 August 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba vil forl\u00e6nge med OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/superligaen/djemba-djemba-vil-forlaenge-med-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=15 May 2012|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> Djemba-Djemba instead left the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mendy og Djemba-Djemba forlader OB|url=http://www.bold.dk/nyt/Mendy-og-Djemba-Djemba-forlader-OB|publisher=Bold.dk|language=Danish|date=24 May 2012|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> The year before, Djemba-Djemba, along with [[Peter Utaka]], had been told by the club's officials that their contracts would not be renewed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Avis: Djemba-Djemba og Utaka forlader OB|url=http://www.bt.dk/superligaen/avis-djemba-djemba-og-utaka-forlader-ob|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=25 November 2011|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> As a result of their contracts not being renewed, the club decided to release players sooner rather than later.<ref>{{cite news|title=OB: Overvejer salg af Utaka og Djemba|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Hapoel Tel Aviv===\nOn 14 August 2012, Djemba-Djemba signed a two-year contract with Israeli club [[Hapoel Tel Aviv F.C.|Hapoel Tel Aviv]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Djemba-Djemba signed for Hapoel: I found a warm home |url=http://www.one.co.il/Article/204294.html |language=Hebrew |publisher=ONE |date=14 August 2012 |accessdate=14 August 2012 }}</ref> Djemba-Djemba played a total of 28 league games with the [[Tel Aviv]]-based team.\n\n===Partizan===\nOn 24 July 2013, Djemba-Djemba signed a two-year contract with [[Serbia]]n side [[FK Partizan|Partizan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0110emba \u0110emba potpisao za \u0160ampione |url=http://www.sr.partizan.rs/67900-67900/ |language=Serbian |publisher=partizan.rs |date=24 July 2013 |accessdate=24 July 2013}}</ref> He made his debut in a Champions League qualifying match away to [[PFC Ludogorets Razgrad|Ludogorets Razgrad]] on 31 July 2013, coming on as a substitute in the 64th minute.<ref>http://www.mozzartsport.com/vesti/sale-buljavi-brate-moj</ref> However, Djemba-Djemba hardly played for Partizan during the first half of the season. The club's signing of [[Nikola Drin\u010di\u0107]] on 20 December meant that Djemba-Djemba became surplus to requirements and his contract was terminated on 23 December 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Partizan raskinuo ugovor sa \u0110emba \u0110embom |trans-title=Partizan terminated the contract with Djemba Djemba |url=http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/sport.294.html:469954-Partizan-raskinuo-ugovor-sa-Djemba-Djembom |work=Novosti.rs |publisher=Kompanija Novosti |date=23 December 2013 |accessdate=23 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nUpon joining St Mirren, Djemba-Djemba once went on three month unpaid at the club.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren midfielder Eric Djemba-Djemba keen to extend his stay in Scottish football|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/st-mirren-midfielder-eric-djemba-djemba-3222651?|publisher=Daily Record|date=9 March 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===St Mirren===\nOn 5 February 2014, Djemba-Djemba signed a short-term deal with [[Scottish Premiership]] club [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Saints sign Djemba-Djemba |url=http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=30679 |publisher=saintmirren.net |date=5 February 2014 |accessdate=5 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221233146/http://www.saintmirren.net/pages/?p=30679 |archivedate=21 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He has said he hopes his move to St Mirren can help him gain a place in the [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] in [[Brazil]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Eric Djemba-Djemba hopes St Miren move can force a World cup place |url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/st-mirren/263108-eric-djemba-djemba-hopes-st-mirren-move-can-force-a-world-cup-place/ |publisher=STV Sport |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=6 February 2014 }}</ref> Upon joining the club, Manager [[Danny Lennon]] described Djemba-Djemba as the club's biggest signing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eric Djemba Djemba is St Mirren's biggest signing ever according to manager Danny Lennon|url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/458429/Eric-Djemba-Djemba-is-St-Mirren-s-biggest-signing-ever-according-to-manager-Danny-Lennon|publisher=Daily Express|date=6 February 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nDjemba-Djemba made his debut for the club, in the [[2013\u201314 Scottish Cup#Fifth round|fifth round of the Scottish Cup]], as St Mirren lost 2\u20131 against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]. After making just three appearances in all competitions, Djemba-Djemba was released by the club at the end of the season and also failed to secure a place on the Cameroon squad for the world cup.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27492630 | title=St Mirren: Eric Djemba-Djemba among Buddies departures | publisher=bbc.co.uk | date=20 May 2014 | accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Chennaiyin FC===\nIn October 2014, Djemba-Djemba signed a short-term deal with [[Indian Super League]] club [[Chennaiyin FC]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Prasad|first1=Vishnu|title=Former United Star Joins Chennaiyin in Late Movement|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/sport/Former-United-Star-Joins-Chennaiyin-in-Late-Movement/2014/10/20/article2486275.ece|work=The New Indian Express|accessdate=28 October 2014|date=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Persebaya Bhayangkara===\nIn February 2015, Djemba-Djemba signed for [[Indonesian Super League]] club Persebaya Bhayangkara.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ini Nilai Kontrak Eric Djemba-Djemba Di Persebaya Surabaya |trans-title= |first=Farabi |last=Firdausy |work=Goal |date=3 February 2015 |access-date=29 December 2018 |url= https://www.goal.com/id/news/1391/liga-1-indonesia/2015/02/03/8567132/ini-nilai-kontrak-eric-djemba-djemba-di-persebaya-surabaya |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Eric Djemba-Djemba Akhirnya Gabung Latihan Persebaya |work=TRIBUNnews.com |date=4 February 2015 |accessdate=29 December 2018 |url= http://www.tribunnews.com/superball/2015/02/04/eric-djemba-djemba-akhirnya-gabung-latihan-persebaya}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nDjemba-Djemba was a member of the [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon team]] that won the [[2002 African Nations Cup]] and finished as runners-up to France at the [[2003 FIFA Confederations Cup]]. While in the Confederations Cup, Djemba-Djemba revealed that he was the last person to have a conversation with [[Marc-Vivien Fo\u00e9]] before Fo\u00e9 collapsed on the pitch and later died in the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren's Eric Djemba-Djemba on Marc-Vivien Foe|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/latest/st-mirren-s-eric-djemba-djemba-on-marc-vivien-foe-1-3299667|publisher=The Scotsman|date=9 February 2014|accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref> He also appeared at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]]. However, Djemba-Djemba wasn't included for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]], due to managerial differences.<ref>{{cite news|title=Djemba-Djemba kommer ikke til VM|url=http://www.bt.dk/fodbold/djemba-djemba-kommer-ikke-til-vm|publisher=BT.dk|language=Danish|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> Despite his attempt to make the Cameroon squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]], Djemba-Djemba wasn't included in the 28-man provisional World Cup squad and thus missing out on the World Cup under the management of [[Volker Finke]].<ref>{{cite news|title=World Cup 2014: Cameroon coach picks familiar line-up|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27374746|publisher=BBC Sport|date=12 May 2014|accessdate=12 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nDjemba-Djemba was born in [[Douala]], Cameroon.<ref name=Hugman/> He was declared bankrupt following his move from Manchester United to Aston Villa in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ten 4x4s, 30 bank accounts...but Eric lost it all|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-484203/Premier-League-Rumour-Mill-West-Ham-want-Brazilian-wonderkid.html|publisher=Daily Mail|date=13 March 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nDjemba-Djemba was married and fathered four children before being divorced.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eric Djemba-Djemba was on \u00a375k-a-month at Man United.. but every penny was going on loan repayments, reveals St Mirren new boy's ex-agent|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/eric-djemba-djemba-75k-a-month-man-united-3116850|publisher=Daily Record|date=6 February 2014|accessdate=21 March 2014}}</ref> Djemba-Djemba is a [[Christians|Christian]].<ref>{{cite news |title=St Mirren new boy Eric Djemba-Djemba: I've lost millions.. but now I'm a simple man who takes the train and eats at KFC and enjoys sea bass on occasion. |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/st-mirren-new-boy-eric-3120241 |publisher=Daily Record |date=7 February 2014 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n;Manchester United\n*[[FA Cup]]: [[2004 FA Cup Final|2003\u201304]]\n*[[FA Community Shield]]: [[2003 FA Community Shield|2003]]\n\n===International===\n;Cameroon\n*[[Africa Cup of Nations]]: [[2002 African Cup of Nations|2002]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{FootballDatabase.eu|299}}\n* [http://www.danskfodbold.com/spiller.php?ligaid=2001&spillerid=11165 Career statistics] at danskfodbold.com {{in lang|da}}\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{Soccerway|eric-djemba-djemba/2805}}\n* {{NFT|1255<!-- /Eric_Djemba_Djemba -->}}\n* {{UEFA player}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|bg = Green\n|fg = Yellow\n|title = Cameroon squads\n|list1 =\n{{Cameroon Squad 2002 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Cameroon Squad 2002 World Cup}}\n{{Cameroon Squad Confederations Cup 2003}}\n{{Cameroon Squad 2004 African Nations Cup}}\n{{Cameroon Squad 2006 Africa Cup of Nations}}}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Djemba-Djemba, Eric}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Douala]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian Christians]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian footballers]]\n[[Category:Cameroon international footballers]]\n[[Category:Kadji Sports Academy players]]\n[[Category:FC Nantes players]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aston Villa F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Burnley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Qatar SC players]]\n[[Category:Odense Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Hapoel Tel Aviv F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FK Partizan players]]\n[[Category:St Mirren F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Chennaiyin FC players]]\n[[Category:Persebaya Surabaya players]]\n[[Category:Voltigeurs de Ch\u00e2teaubriant players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Israeli Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Serbian SuperLiga players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Indian Super League players]]\n[[Category:Liga 1 (Indonesia) players]]\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2003 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:2002 African Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2004 African Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2006 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Israel]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in India]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Qatar]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Israel]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian expatriate sportspeople in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Qatar Stars League players]]\n", "name_user": "62.254.110.97", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Djemba-Djemba"}
{"title_page": "Manish Borundia", "text_new": "{{Short description|Indian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| Name = Manish Borundia\n| Caption = Mr.\n| Birth_name = Manish\n| Othername = Akash(In Kannada Films)\n| Birth_date = 01 March 1980\n| Birth_place = [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu, India]]\n| Residence = Bangalore\n| Occupation = Actor and Businessman\n| yearsactive = 1999\u2013present\n| spouse = Anita Manish\n| children = NIL\n| relatives = Anjali (Sister)\n| parents =  Gautham B (Father) / Vinita Gautham (Mother)\n}}\n\n'''Manish Borundia''' is an Indian film actor from Bangalore who has appeared in Lead and Supporting roles in Tamil, Telugu, Hindi and Kannada films.\n\n==Career==\nBorn and brought up in Chennai, Manish began a modelling career while managing his father's business, an established Model coordinator hand picked him for his Smile, Eyes and height..henceforth he  regularly appeared in plenty Commercials and Music videos. He became acquainted and shared a friendship with Ultimate Star [[Ajith Kumar]] during their time as models, and often visited the actor during his film shoots.<ref name=\"mb\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/ajith-sir-introduced-me-to-the-movies-manish-borundia/articleshow/71024795.cms |title=Ajith sir introduced me to the movies: Manish Borundia &#124; Tamil Movie News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-09-08 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref> Ajith requested Manish to play a minor acting role in ''[[Amarkalam]]'' (1999) after the original actor did not turn up, and thus Manish made his first on-screen appearance. In the early 2000s, Manish continued to portray supporting roles in Tamil films, often as the lead actor's friends, and notably appeared in [[S. J. Surya]]'s ''[[Kushi (2000 film)|Kushi]]'' (2000), [[Saran (director)|Saran]]'s ''[[Parthen Rasithen]]'' (2000), [[Gautham Menon]]'s ''[[Minnale]]'' (2001) and [[Jeeva (director)|Jeeva]]'s ''[[12B]]'' (2001).<ref name=\"mb\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nameeta.co.in/rendezvous-with-manish-borundia/ |title=Rendezvous with Manish Borundia &#124; Nameeta Renchi |publisher=Nameeta.co.in |date=2018-01-22 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Thandoratimes.com |url=https://thandoratimes.com/news-id-this-handsome-actor-thanks-ajith-kumar-for-introducing-him-into-acting2198.htm |title=This handsome actor thanks Ajith Kumar for introducing him into acting - Mission Mangal- Ajithkumar- Amarkalam- Manish Borundia |publisher=Thandoratimes.com |date= |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Manish admires actors like Kamal Haasan and Ananth Nag - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/Manish-admires-actors-like-Kamal-Haasan-and-Ananth-Nag/articleshow/33559418.cms |website=The Times of India |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nManish then signed on to appear in the lead role of [[P. C. Sreeram]]'s ''[[Vaanam Vasappadum]]'' (2004) and was attached to the project for six months, before being dropped due to his strong Hindi accent. The role was eventually taken by [[Karthik Kumar]]. Manish starred in his first lead role through the Kannada film ''Jootata'' (2004), appearing alongside [[Sameer Dattani|Dhyan]] and [[Richa Pallod]]. For the project, he took up the stage name of Akash, though the film did not perform well commercially and received negative reviews from critics. But Manish was appreciated for his comic timing. After the movies disappointment he left Overseas for Job and career growth to take care of his dependant family.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jootata review. Jootata Kannada movie review, story, rating |url=https://onlinecareer360.com/ |website=onlinecareer360.com |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On his return to India he signed His second Kannada film, ''Nannusire'', also under performed commercially but Manish's role was described as \"short, sweet and attractive.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Nannusire review. Nannusire Kannada movie review, story, rating |url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/nannusire-review-kannada-movie-10618 |website=IndiaGlitz.com |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> He also portrayed a character in [[Arjun Sarja|Arjun]]'s Tamil and Telugu bilingual film, ''[[Madrasi (2006 film)|Madrasi]]'' (2006). As his acting career failed to take off, Manish took up a job in [[Hong Kong]] before moving to [[Bengaluru]] to continue looking after his family's jewellery business.<ref name=\"mb\"/>\n\nIn 2019, he made a comeback through Jagan Shakti's Hindi drama film ''[[Mission Mangal]]'', based on the life of scientists at the [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] (ISRO) who contributed to the [[Mars Orbiter Mission]]. Featuring among an ensemble cast including [[Akshay Kumar]] and [[Vidya Balan]], Manish appeared in a supporting role of an ISRO HR employee.<ref name=\"mb\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/bengaluru-based-actor-manish-borundia-bags-a-role-in-mission-mangal/articleshow/67406371.cms |title=Bengaluru-based actor Manish Borundia bags a role in Mission Mangal &#124; Kannada Movie News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-01-07 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nStarted taking responsibilities of family at an early age of 16, Manish was a matured and responsible boy of the family. He took over his father's loss making company and turned it profitable. Along this journey South India's leading Model Coordinator set her eyes on his looks, Smile and eyes and offered him his first commercial Ad in 1999 for 5k per day. Seeing the money is exactly his one months house expense he grabbed this opportunity and thus he realised his hidden talent of acting.\nEver since then he has been a house hold face of South Indian TV.\nHaving family to take care he chose Business as his main money earning source and turned Films as hobbies till Luck strikes his once again.\nMarried Anita Lunia in 2015 which his family selected for him and now has opened a Luxury Kids clothing store in Bangalore known as Beautiful Mess in Kumarapark west, Bangalore\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Language\n!Notes\n|-\n|| 1999 || ''[[Amarkalam]]'' || Kidnapped Boy || Tamil ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2000 || ''[[Kushi (2000 film)|Kushi]]'' || Shiva's friend || Tamil ||\n|-\n| ''[[Parthen Rasithen]]'' || Sarika's brother || Tamil ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2001 || ''[[Minnale]]'' || Rajesh's friend || Tamil ||\n|-\n| ''[[12B]]'' || || Tamil || Uncredited\n|-\n| 2005 || ''Jootata'' || Hero || Kannada ||\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Madrasi (2006 film)|Madrasi]]'' || || Tamil ||\n|-\n| 2008 || ''Nannusire'' || || Kannada ||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Mission Mangal]]'' || Kaushal Saini || Hindi ||\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borundia, Manish}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Tamil cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Kannada cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Chennai]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Indian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| Name = Manish Borundia\n| Caption = Mr.\n| Birth_name = Manish\n| Othername = Akash(In Kannada Films)\n| Birth_date = 01 March 1980\n| Birth_place = [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu, India]]\n| Residence = Bangalore\n| Occupation = Actor and Businessman\n| yearsactive = 1999\u2013present\n| spouse = Anita Manish\n| children = NIL\n| relatives = Anjali (Sister)\n| parents =  Gautham B (Father) / Vinita Gautham (Mother)\n}}\n\n'''Manish Borundia''' is an Indian film actor from Bangalore who has appeared in Lead and Supporting roles in Tamil, Telugu, Hindi and Kannada films.\n\n==Career==\nBorn and brought up in Chennai, Manish began a modelling career while managing his father's business, an established Model coordinator hand picked him for his Smile, Eyes and height..henceforth he  regularly appeared in plenty Commercials and Music videos. He became acquainted and shared a friendship with Ultimate Star [[Ajith Kumar]] during their time as models, and often visited the actor during his film shoots.<ref name=\"mb\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/ajith-sir-introduced-me-to-the-movies-manish-borundia/articleshow/71024795.cms |title=Ajith sir introduced me to the movies: Manish Borundia &#124; Tamil Movie News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-09-08 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref> Ajith requested Manish to play a minor acting role in ''[[Amarkalam]]'' (1999) after the original actor did not turn up, and thus Manish made his first on-screen appearance. In the early 2000s, Manish continued to portray supporting roles in Tamil films, often as the lead actor's friends, and notably appeared in [[S. J. Surya]]'s ''[[Kushi (2000 film)|Kushi]]'' (2000), [[Saran (director)|Saran]]'s ''[[Parthen Rasithen]]'' (2000), [[Gautham Menon]]'s ''[[Minnale]]'' (2001) and [[Jeeva (director)|Jeeva]]'s ''[[12B]]'' (2001).<ref name=\"mb\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://nameeta.co.in/rendezvous-with-manish-borundia/ |title=Rendezvous with Manish Borundia &#124; Nameeta Renchi |publisher=Nameeta.co.in |date=2018-01-22 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Thandoratimes.com |url=https://thandoratimes.com/news-id-this-handsome-actor-thanks-ajith-kumar-for-introducing-him-into-acting2198.htm |title=This handsome actor thanks Ajith Kumar for introducing him into acting - Mission Mangal- Ajithkumar- Amarkalam- Manish Borundia |publisher=Thandoratimes.com |date= |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Manish admires actors like Kamal Haasan and Ananth Nag - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/Manish-admires-actors-like-Kamal-Haasan-and-Ananth-Nag/articleshow/33559418.cms |website=The Times of India |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nManish then signed on to appear in the lead role of [[P. C. Sreeram]]'s ''[[Vaanam Vasappadum]]'' (2004) and was attached to the project for six months, before being dropped due to his strong Hindi accent. The role was eventually taken by [[Karthik Kumar]]. Manish starred in his first lead role through the Kannada film ''Jootata'' (2004), appearing alongside [[Sameer Dattani|Dhyan]] and [[Richa Pallod]]. For the project, he took up the stage name of Akash, though the film did not perform well commercially and received negative reviews from critics. But Manish was appreciated for his comic timing. After the movies disappointment he left Overseas for Job and career growth to take care of his dependant family.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jootata review. Jootata Kannada movie review, story, rating |url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/jootata-review-kannada-movie-7865 |website=IndiaGlitz.com |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> On his return to India he signed His second Kannada film, ''Nannusire'', also under performed commercially but Manish's role was described as \"short, sweet and attractive.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Nannusire review. Nannusire Kannada movie review, story, rating |url=https://www.indiaglitz.com/nannusire-review-kannada-movie-10618 |website=IndiaGlitz.com |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref> He also portrayed a character in [[Arjun Sarja|Arjun]]'s Tamil and Telugu bilingual film, ''[[Madrasi (2006 film)|Madrasi]]'' (2006). As his acting career failed to take off, Manish took up a job in [[Hong Kong]] before moving to [[Bengaluru]] to continue looking after his family's jewellery business.<ref name=\"mb\"/>\n\nIn 2019, he made a comeback through Jagan Shakti's Hindi drama film ''[[Mission Mangal]]'', based on the life of scientists at the [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] (ISRO) who contributed to the [[Mars Orbiter Mission]]. Featuring among an ensemble cast including [[Akshay Kumar]] and [[Vidya Balan]], Manish appeared in a supporting role of an ISRO HR employee.<ref name=\"mb\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/kannada/movies/news/bengaluru-based-actor-manish-borundia-bags-a-role-in-mission-mangal/articleshow/67406371.cms |title=Bengaluru-based actor Manish Borundia bags a role in Mission Mangal &#124; Kannada Movie News - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2019-01-07 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nStarted taking responsibilities of family at an early age of 16, Manish was a matured and responsible boy of the family. He took over his father's loss making company and turned it profitable. Along this journey South India's leading Model Coordinator set her eyes on his looks, Smile and eyes and offered him his first commercial Ad in 1999 for 5k per day. Seeing the money is exactly his one months house expense he grabbed this opportunity and thus he realised his hidden talent of acting.\nEver since then he has been a house hold face of South Indian TV.\nHaving family to take care he chose Business as his main money earning source and turned Films as hobbies till Luck strikes his once again.\nMarried Anita Lunia in 2015 which his family selected for him and now has opened a Luxury Kids clothing store in Bangalore known as Beautiful Mess in Kumarapark west, Bangalore\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Language\n!Notes\n|-\n|| 1999 || ''[[Amarkalam]]'' || Kidnapped Boy || Tamil ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2000 || ''[[Kushi (2000 film)|Kushi]]'' || Shiva's friend || Tamil ||\n|-\n| ''[[Parthen Rasithen]]'' || Sarika's brother || Tamil ||\n|-\n| rowspan=